We visited last week to allow him to pass peacefully as he had become suddenly very unwell with something untreatable.

Are you a Caregiver for someone with a serious illness during this holiday season? 

We know how it difficult it is to care for those with serious illness any time of the year, but the holidays often add more difficulty and stress. 

Swipe ‚û°Ô∏è to see our tips for you. 

What are you doing this holiday season to reduce your stress?

There‚Äôs a fire in my belly to share my beautiful work‚Ä¶..

This is my first in a series of workshops to be held in Ballan at Susie Verity‚Äôs beautiful yoga and workshop space. 

Doulabarb (Barb Ferguson) has many years experience guiding families with end of life care, join her for this gentle workshop on caring for and guiding your loved ones end of life and after death care. Gain knowledge about the choices available to you for the setting of the death, home, hospital or hospice. Be immersed in a day of ceremony and ritual with a hands on session of shrouding for burial or cremation. 

Learn how you can gently hold and step into your grief incorporating it into our everyday life going forward. 

Participants will leave comforted by a new can do attitude towards living and dying well. #deathliteracy#shrouding #shrouds #endoflife #endoflifecareplan #endoflifecare

This app streamlines end of life care planning into a series of yes/no questions that helps you figure out what decisions you need to make and what services you need to support you in making them. I haven't tried it, but it sounds promising. Have you tried this yet?

The co-founder, Suelin Chen, was studying engineering to develop medical technology to treat prostate cancer when she learned what so many healthcare professionals already know, "...the fact that more medical interventions are not necessarily better for the patient, yet our healthcare system is not set up in a way for these types of conversations to happen. Patient‚Äôs families have to either be extremely proactive advocates, or you have to get lucky and encounter a clinician that will present your options in a clear way." This is something that came up during our last meeting of Waking Death. Someone asked, if I don't have a friend or family member who is a trained healthcare professional to advocate for me, how do I figure out what quality of life means to me and what types of care I want to support that? Unless you have a terminal diagnosis, your insurance will not permit you to consult with a palliative care doctor who is trained to facilitate this conversation.

An end of life doula can support you with tools such as reflective questions, active listening, meditative exercises to help you understand what you need to find comfort and quality in your final years, months, or days of life. They can help you develop a plan and point you to resources to help you put your vision into action.

‚ÄòTis a fearful thing
to love what death can touch.

A fearful thing
to love, to hope, to dream, to be ‚Äì

to be,
And oh, to lose.

A thing for fools, this,

And a holy thing,

a holy thing
to love.

For your life has lived in me,
your laugh once lifted me,
your word was gift to me.

To remember this brings painful joy. ‚ÄòTis a human thing, love,
a holy thing, to love
what death has touched.

Judah Halevi

So I had a lovely morning this morning going swimming üèäüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è but then I had a meeting with my Ty Hafan Family Support Worker... whilst I adore Tracey, and our meeting was definitely mostly full of discussion about all the positives in my life, we had the start of a difficult conversation about updating my end of life care plans. Whilst I update my Advance Directive, the legal documents, regularly, I haven‚Äôt actually updated my end of life care plan, which includes things like my funeral plan, since my early teens. Tracey recommended we book another day a few weeks from now to actually type it all up; on the meantime, I‚Äôm to have a think about what I want and write it all down in my trusty butterfly notebook. I spent an hour this evening on the bench in my garden writing in said notebook. I stopped when I got too upset to continue.
Anyway, I‚Äôd had a tough time! So, the two lovely carers working today decided that me and my housemates should go on a walk to Victoria Park in Canton and have fish n chips! It was an excellent plan, and really cheered me up (even though my bloody wheelchair broke down at the park and LMC had to come pick us up üôàüòÇ ALAC are coming to fix it first thing tomorrow) üòÅ‚ù§Ô∏è
I must say that whilst I‚Äôm incredibly lucky to have such amazing friends and family, I‚Äôm especially lucky that I have such amazing carers and nurses here at LMC taking such great care of me. Danni and Rhi, my carers today, knew exactly when to talk about my end of life care plan, and when to avoid the subject entirely. They knew being outside, in the sun, near nature, with people, would cheer me up. They knew fish and chips would help (especially because I hadn‚Äôt eaten all day because of feeling so anxious). And they made me laugh! And when they left today, they both have me a massive hug ü§ó. I‚Äôm just really glad I have such wonderful, kind people looking after me ‚ù§Ô∏è and I‚Äôm sending a big thank you to them both!

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

Our Platinum Package includes a number of services to help you plan for the end of your life (For example: funeral planning, bureaucratic and administrative work, repatriations, death certificates and body reclaiming, body donation to science, and so on).
You can also get help completing an advance directive (in portuguese called Diretiva Antecipada de Vontade, DAV/RENTEV) or living will, which is a document in which individuals state their preferences regarding the healthcare they want to receive if they are in a medical condition where they are unable to express their wishes.
Because unexpected end-of-life situations can occur at any age, it is important that everyone is aware that they can have a say right up until the end if they so desire.
This allows you to receive the medical care you want to have, avoid unnecessary suffering, and relieve family members of decision-making responsibilities during times of crisis or grief.
The living will also name one or two people as healthcare proxies, who can decide what healthcare a person will or will not receive if their medical condition prevents them from expressing their own wishes.
üìåWho can make a living will?
A living will can be made by anyone, including portuguese citizens, non-nationals, and refugees (stateless people), as long as they are residents in Portugal, of legal age, and are not incapacitated by any mental impairment.
If you want to learn more about the RENTEV form and/or all of the other end-of-life services available at imergencies, please contact us at info@ecde.org.

This is ED, an old boy struggling to make it through winter.

Our temperatures are starting to plummet as an arctic storm takes over. 

He is a thoroughbred, which means he has thin skin and thin hair and has been struggling to keep the weight on. His vet checks are clean, teeth look good, he's been de-wormed... 

His mom said he has been "off" for the past week and wasn't sure what to do. 

She asked me to connect with him and see if it was time to say goodbye or if he wanted to try and make it through the storm. 

She is hoping to bring him home in one week and wanted me to pass that message on to him.

This was his response...

"I'm not quite ready to go yet. I know it pains my mom to see me like this but it's not as bad as it looks, I can withstand the weather. It is cold though. I know it's not quite time yet. I want to try and make it home." 

Though he isn't ready to say his goodbyes yet...the time is approaching and he had a few requests. 

He asked that his mom spend quiet time, alone with him. He wanted to have a photo shoot with her so she could have a nice picture of the two of them for her wall. 

He also asked that she leave something with him, something special. 

He sent me an image of a feather. She knew exactly what he was talking about. The feather in his mane is a special feather they found together that she has kept for years.

She sent me a text the following day after my conversation with Ed and she said he looked much brighter and he was ready for his photo shoot! :)

It is such an honor to be able to check in with your companions as they near the end of their physical life.

It‚Äôs this exact story I have personally lived through many times and that‚Äôs why I created my Peaceful Transitions sessions. If you want answers to those questions please reach out I‚Äôd love to help ‚ù§Ô∏èyou can head over to the website (link in bio) or DM me.

Gaining clarity--being fully present for pain--making choices from our highest selves

How this is playing out as we care for our aging cat in the end stages of his life-->
Our guy Buster is likely 15+ years old according to our vet's best estimate. We found him on petfinder at our local humane society almost 5 years ago where he was awaiting a forever home for a couple of years. 
Buster's personality is a blend of some of our favorite aspects of two dearly departed cats, Ozzy & Fergus, so he fit right in with our preference for a mature, less frisky cat. 
As he is this morning beginning a noticeable decline in mobility & has begun hiding, my husband & I began discussing whether or not "it's time." We both agree that we wish for Buster to remain here in our home to pass as peacefully as possible on his own terms in his favorite spots as long as he isn't suffering. We were both quite emotional and I began digging into options for his end of life care. 
Did you know there are hospice care veterinarians? They are trained to counsel families on the options available for each pet based on their current condition. I'm absolutely amazed to find a local practitioner and the fact that there is an option I wasn't aware of has brought me comfort. 
I brought Buster outside to our patio where he's moving from chair to rug and soaking up the sun. I'm grateful to be able to attend to his needs as we consider next steps while monitoring him.

Just the shift in my energy & getting him into the fresh air is seemingly bringing him peace as well. 
I'm remaining present to what is...taking in our time together and will allow clarity to arrive as we ready ourselves for Buster's transition to the rainbow bridge. üòø

‚ú®Update on Amelia ‚ú®
.
We found out on Sunday that what the vets have been treating as a chronic UTI has not been a UTI at all, rather Amelia has a large mass inside of her bladder that has been responding to and shrinking with the antiinflammatories we have been giving her. As soon as she comes off of the medicines the mass gets bigger again and she can not urinate. We cannot afford to do surgery nor would I be willing to put her through the pain at 15 years old. We made the decision with the vet to essential be Amelia's hospice care. We will be giving her the meds and pain meds to keep her comfortable as well. The vet doesn't believe it's time yet due to here being in good health otherwise and great spirits on the medicines. Im keeping a very close eye on her and as soon as she shows the first sign that she is ready we will make the decision to end her pain.
 .
So for what little time we do have left Miss Amelia is getting wet food every night, lots of cuddles and all the play time she wants. üíñüòª Thank you for all your love and positive energy and prayers. ü•∞

Some comfy sweaters on the floor makes a nice spot for him to rest the rest of the week. Pet hospice care for another 5.5 days and caring for my little muffin as best I can. I ask you all keep him in your prayers and send him comforting energy, anything is appreciated right now.

This week, I made a difficult decision in my cat's care. After consulting with her vet, I decided to shift from treatment that cures to treatment that comforts. The vet has marked her chart "hospice."¬†

This delightfully sweet cat has loved me for seventeen years. Our relationship is the longest, most intimate friendship I've ever had. She's seen me at my worst and at my best. In the time that we've been together, I've gone through all of the major life transitions with her at my side: moving, graduating college, marriage, divorce, having kids, starting new jobs.

She loves on the boys, and she has truly been our emotional support cat during¬†COVID. She snuggles and licks me when I'm sad. She makes me laugh, because she is such a weirdo.¬†

Anticipatory grief. 

The grief that isn‚Äôt spoken about. 
So what is it?

In short, Anticipatory grief is the grief you feel before a person has died. You‚Äôre grieving the current situation, the person they were, the life you had, and all the memories all at once. It can show up in a magnitude of ways, e.g. constant sadness (low mood), fear, guilt, anxiety, or physical symptoms such as: loss of appetite, trouble sleeping, pain in your chest, irritability, and so much more.

As someone supporting a griever, how can I help? 

‚Ä¢ Make them a meal (Curry, soup, Mac & cheese, lasagne, spag bowl, anything!)

‚Ä¢ Lend a hand with physical work e.g cleaning the bathrooms / kitchen / running errands / grabbing groceries.

‚Ä¢ Plan an outdoor activity with them (A walk, picnic)

‚Ä¢ Listen. Don‚Äôt try fix their grief. Just listen. 

‚Ä¢ Avoid statements like ‚Äúeverything happens for a reason‚Äù. Insensitive and shows ignorance. Instead focus on their feelings, and hold space for them to just be.

‚Ä¢ Send them a message. Not to have a good day. Rather, to have a day. Say you‚Äôre checking in to see they‚Äôve done their teeth, or managed to make the bed, or perhaps had a bite to eat. It‚Äôs not disregarding ‚Äògood‚Äô days, it‚Äôs being realistic and helping them achieve mundane tasks that feel so hard. 

‚Ä¢ Continue showing up for them. You don‚Äôt need to be perfect, simply present.

Educate yourself, be patient & show compassion. 

Hope this helps ‚ô•Ô∏è

Just wanted to say hello and good morning ‚ù§Ô∏è I have been asked recently what it means to be #deathpositive , and I wanted to share with you what that means. To put it simply‚Ä¶it means to speak about death openly like it is a normal, inevitable thing. It‚Äôs going to happen to everyone. It means having conversations around death, and not treating it like a taboo subject. Being death positive helps us confront our fears of mortality. It‚Äôs acceptance over denial. Reposted from @barbarakarnesrn Not eating and reduced fluid intake as part of the normal dying process that occurs months before death from disease is Hospice 101.

It is imperative for every hospice employee working with patients and families at end of life to be comfortable and knowledgable in end of life nutrition. So here is Hospice 101 nutrition:

Months before death from disease (add years for old age) a person‚Äôs eating habits change. It begins with not wanting to eat meat, then fruits and vegetables, graduating to soft foods, then liquid supplements, then basically nothing.

Food is the body‚Äôs anchor to this planet. It is what keeps us going, gives us energy, grounds us. As death from disease approaches the body doesn‚Äôt want the grounding, the energy that food gives. The body is releasing its hold on living. It is food that keeps us alive so the body gradually stops eating.

It isn‚Äôt that the person doesn‚Äôt want to eat, they can‚Äôt eat. They try to eat for us but gradually, ever so slowly, they just stop eating.

At this point the entire body is shutting down (generally weeks before death) and physiologically the body is not functioning normally. If at this time you begin forcing food with TPN or feeding tubes/gastrostomy you will generally end up with more complications than benefit---because the body doesn‚Äôt want the food.

About this time, a week or so before death, a person is not taking enough fluids for hydration. Again, the body is letting go, it doesn‚Äôt want or need the hydration. Giving IV fluids at this point only increases congestion in the lungs, fluid builds up in the body (the kidneys are not working properly now), creating discomfort.

Yes, people dying from disease die being dehydrated. The interesting aspect to dehydration is that as the calcium in the blood stream builds from the dehydration, a person just goes to sleep and doesn‚Äôt wake up. Isn‚Äôt this how most people want to die? ‚ÄúI just want to close my eyes and not wake up‚Äù is the death of choice.  #endoflifecaregiver #endoflifedoula #eol #deathdoula #caregiver  #foodatendoflife #caregiving  #endoflifeeducation #hospicesocialworker #hospicechaplain #hospicecare #hospicenurse #hospice #d
#hospice #hospicenurse #eoldoula #families #cancer #dying #death #chaplains #deathdoula #endoflife #endoflifecaregiver #caregiver

When a Loved One is dying, it can be very stressful. Emotions are running high, everyone is tired and sad.

It can be very tempting to let your feelings run the show, let loose and say whatever comes to mind to release some internal pressure.

But please ‚Äì this is so important ‚Äì keep the peace with your family, whether that‚Äôs siblings, your parents, your kids, or in-laws. I agree, it‚Äôs not easy! 

Even if someone else lets loose on you, do your best not to react. Choose to take a breath and leave the room for a minute. 

While in the other room, breathe in through your nose and out through your mouth. Focused, deep breaths slow you down and can help diffuse big emotions. 

You can also try grounding yourself: 
üëÅÔ∏è What are five things you can see?
ü¶ª What are four things you can hear?
ü´± What are three things you can feel?
üëÉ What are two things you can smell?
üëÖ What is one thing you can taste? 

Water is also helpful ‚Äì go to the bathroom and run cold water on your hands and splash some cold water on your face or get a drink of water.

Everyone handles difficult circumstances differently, whether or not we like it or understand it. One person may cry, someone else gets angry or seems indifferent.

There may also be other things going on in their lives that are weighing on them, that we know nothing about and have nothing to do with the person who is dying.

Even if it may not appear so, people can be hurting deeply inside, no matter their outward behavior. 

Much Love, Lili ‚ù§Ô∏è

If we're lucky, we have time to say goodbye before someone we love dies.

It can be really difficult to know how to have these conversations. What's the right thing to say? How and when should I say it?

Having a structure like this helps you find the strength to say what needs to be said, even though it's hard and sad.

Yesterday our Acting CEO Carol Raye gratefully received funds from @queenslandgives ‚ù§ for much-needed training equipment for our Palliative care nursing team. 

The funds were used to purchase specialised training equipment for our Clinical Nursing team including a Catheterisation and Enema trainer, an Automated External Defibrillator (AED) Trainer and a CPR Mannequin, as well as two syringe drivers which will be used in our Outreach Service.

Syringe Drivers are important devices in end-of-life care as they help to avoid having to give injected medicines frequently, therefore increasing the quality of care for the patient.

At Katie Rose Cottage Hospice, we strive to provide the highest quality end-of-life care, and training of our team is an integral part of this strategy. 

Our services are provided at NO COST, providing equitable access to all. 

Our Hospice care enables our guests to spend their final days with dignity and respect and provides the opportunity for friends and family to relinquish the role of carer and spend time with them and farewell their loved ones, in a peaceful and comfortable environment.

Dominant culture separates us from death, so many of us have never been present at a deathbed. Or if we have, we might have known what to expect, or how to cooperate with the archetypal wisdom of the dying process. 

A deathbed is a liminal zone, a threshold between this world and the next. It's a profoundly sacred space, and what happens there can have big implications for both the living and the dying. 

If a deathbed is held well, the dying person is supported in letting go of their physical body and reorienting their life force energy to the next step in their journey. The living are supported to feel both their love and their grief, and to say a whole-hearted goodbye to physical life with there loved one in it. 

My latest course, "Holding Space at a Deathbed: How to support a dying person as their body and soul separate" is for dying people, caregivers, death doulas and other end-of-life practitioners. It's a pragmatic spiritual guide to the last weeks of life. 

Find more details at the link in my bio

In episode 84 of Seeing Death Clearly my guest Jill Bodak shares the deeply personal story of her father‚Äôs stroke in 2020, which flipped her world upside down. 

Initially told that he wouldn‚Äôt survive, her father defied the odds but was left in a severely compromised state, requiring Jill to become his primary caregiver.

Over time, her father expressed that he no longer wanted to live, which led them to explore medically assisted death, a legal option in Canada. 

Jill‚Äôs writing throughout this period focused on family, grief, and caregiving. 

Her book, Loved Into Being: Reflections on Stroke and Being Indestructible, emerged as both a tribute and a conversation starter on end-of-life rights.

She speaks about the emotional complexity of caregiving and the challenging role reversal, explaining that her father's vulnerability during his illness was a beautiful yet heartbreaking contrast to the physically active person he once was. 

In this clip, she talks about the bond they had. 
‚ÄúThere wasn't anything I felt like we couldn't do‚Ä¶ looking back, I'm like, oh, he could really hardly say anything. That communication had so much to do with our bond and our ability to be vulnerable and close to each other and like, wrestle it out. Like we're gonna figure each other out and even if it takes a really long time.‚Äù

The journey through her father‚Äôs illness and eventual medically assisted death was both transformative and filled with moments of profound connection.

Her story offers a touching and honest look at caregiving, family dynamics, and the complex emotional landscape of end-of-life decisions.

Using forms like this are a FANTASTIC way to soothe resistance when having discussions about end-of-life and/or advanced directives.
‚Ä¢
This tool that gently eases people into the process, by it‚Äôs ‚Äúunofficial‚Äù nature, is a document created by the Funeral Consumers Alliance of Central Texas. It‚Äôs a worksheet that aides in the conversation about what treatments you WOULD or would NOT want in situations where you could not speak for yourself. There are 6 scenarios where you get to choose desired treatments. 
‚Ä¢
It‚Äôs an incredibly helpful document because it really makes you think... and get clear about your wishes. You may find that your responses are quite different for each situation‚Äî or you may come to find something totally different that surprises you.
‚Ä¢
The point is that we are all going to withdraw from this physical experience some day, and there are many decisions to be made as the process unfolds. This worksheet is a great place to start. 
‚Ä¢
Visit, www.fcactx.org to print off the worksheet. For folks in other states, I like to think your nearest Funeral Consumers Alliance would have something similar. If not, it doesn‚Äôt hurt to refer to this one ‚ù§Ô∏è

topPosts.caption:
Hypnosis can be a helpful complementary therapy for people with life-limiting illnesses by providing relief from physical, emotional, and psychological symptoms. Some of the key benefits include:

	1.	Pain Management: Hypnosis can help reduce pain perception by altering the brain‚Äôs response to pain signals. This can be particularly useful for those experiencing chronic or severe pain, often associated with life-limiting illnesses like cancer or neurological disorders.
	2.	Anxiety and Stress Reduction: Facing a life-limiting illness can bring on anxiety, stress, and depression. Hypnosis can help induce a state of deep relaxation, helping to reduce feelings of fear and anxiety. This can also improve overall quality of life.
	3.	Improved Sleep: Many people with serious illnesses struggle with insomnia or restless sleep. Hypnosis can help them relax and create a positive mental environment for better sleep.
	4.	Coping with Emotional Challenges: Hypnosis can help patients process emotional burdens such as fear of dying, grief, or unresolved conflicts, offering a space for mental clarity and emotional relief.
	5.	Symptom Management: Hypnosis may alleviate other symptoms such as nausea, fatigue, or breathlessness.
	6.	Empowerment and Control: For patients who feel a loss of control due to their illness, hypnosis can provide a sense of empowerment, giving them mental tools to cope better with their situation.

While it doesn‚Äôt replace medical treatments, hypnosis can serve as an adjunct therapy that improves a patient‚Äôs overall well-being ü´∂üèº #hypnosisforpain #hypnosisforanxiety #hypnosis #hypnosisduringcancertreatment #hypnosissydney #brainpower #thedeparturecoach #endoflifedoula #endoflifecare #endoflifecareplanning #endoflifepreparedness

Here's a perfect question we can ask ourselves:

"Do I have a plan in place that protects me if I ever end up in a hospital and can't advocate for myself, whether due to serious illness or incapacitation?"

This article was written by a doctor about a situation he had with his dad, who's also a doctor, to give us a perfect perspective on why end-of-life care planning is vital for all of us. 

Whenever your loved ones is on the verge of a serious illness, most of us put too much trust in hospitals and doctors to get us (and our loved ones) through it without considering the emotional, mental health, spiritual, and social needs that may impact our loved ones and ourselves - which is what a "palliative care plan" is all about. And many doctors today are not trained on palliative care options, so they rarely offer it as a possible option when dealing with a loved one's terminal illness. 

You can incorporate a palliative plan in any advanced health care directive to put the right people in charge with the right information on your end-of-life decisions.

We plan for our clients to have the best life possible, and having an end-of-life care plan will give you and your family peace of mind without crisis. Check out this article to understand one doctor's perspective on the importance of this kind of planning.
www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/01/we-protected-my-terminally-ill-father-system/604312/

So today‚Äôs theme for Dying Matters Week is memorialisation, and I just happened to have a meeting with my Ty Hafan Family Support Worker to discuss my end of life care plan. That resulted in me spending an hour or so in the garden this evening writing down everything to do with my dying, death and funeral that came to mind. I stopped when I started to get a bit upset. 
For as long as I can remember, anything I‚Äôve written like this has gone in my butterfly ü¶ã notebook üìí. I‚Äôve had it since I was 14 and writing my first set of care plans. I think it‚Äôs incredibly important that I have a safe place where I can write down all these thoughts üí≠ and also that my loved ones know where to find these thoughts, should they need to read them.

Why Are We So Afraid to Talk About Palliative Care?

A viral video by @drjrubinstein highlights an uncomfortable truth: many people and even healthcare providers resist the idea of palliative care. Why? Because it forces us to confront mortality, grief, and the realities of serious illness‚Äîtopics we often avoid.

Palliative care isn‚Äôt about giving up; it‚Äôs about living as fully and comfortably as possible during life‚Äôs most challenging moments. It offers support, dignity, and relief, yet the stigma around death and dying often prevents us from embracing this compassionate form of care.

We need to change the narrative. Talking about death doesn‚Äôt make it come faster‚Äîit makes it more meaningful. Let‚Äôs normalize these conversations, for ourselves, our families, and our communities.

Thank you, @drjrubinstein, for opening the door to this vital discussion.

#PalliativeCare #EndOfLifeCare #GriefAndTrauma #DeathPositive #HealthcareReform #CompassionateCare #QualityOfLife

@synthesisinstitute ‚ÄúDeath is absolutely safe. It‚Äôs like taking off a tight shoe.‚Äù ‚Äì Ram Dass

In our Western culture, where death is often associated with fear, anxiety, grief, and loss, the topic can feel uncomfortable to approach. 

Yet, across cultures and through an emerging body of scientific research, psychedelics have been explored as potential tools for transforming our relationship with mortality. 

Could these substances open us to a different perspective‚Äîone that fosters a gentler, more accepting view of life‚Äôs end?

Substances like psilocybin, DMT, and ayahuasca have been used for centuries by Indigenous cultures as sacraments of connection. 

In these settings, they‚Äôre believed to help individuals transcend the boundaries of the self and access a sense of unity with the universe. 

From this perspective, death may be seen not as an end, but as a phase in a larger cycle of existence.

What might it mean to reconnect with these ancient practices? Could psychedelics offer us a renewed perspective on the nature of life and death? 

While questions remain, these experiences invite us to reflect on what it means to approach life‚Äôs transitions with curiosity, openness, and peace.

The very best thing you could do to free your loved one from the burden of making these decisions is to create an Advance Directive. Documentation requirements vary from state to state, but it basically allows you to convey your preferences to a medical team in the event that you cannot communicate them yourself.

To clarify, in this video, I‚Äôm talking about people who have suffered catastrophic, irreversible damage, not someone who is acutely ill and has the chance of making a meaningful recovery.

In the days before death, dying people sometimes start connecting with loved ones who have already died. These beings show up in dreams and visions and are as real as any living person. 

If you've been present when this is happening, it can sound like listening to one side of a phone conversation, because the dying person is attuned to a dimension of reality that the living can't access. The veil is thinning and they're starting to move between dimensions. 

Knowing what this kind of speech sounds like, and how to respond to it can make a big difference in how you are able to support a dying person. 

If you're interested in learning more about the spiritual and energetic dynamics of the dying process, check out my new course, Holding Space at a Deathbed. It's a handbook for supporting dying people and their families as the veil thins. 

Find all the details at the link in my bio.

it‚Äôs NEVER too early to talk about any type of Grief ü¶ã | idc who disagrees, I will say this though: if someone is ‚Äúestranged‚Äù from their immediate parents (mom, dad) or family - mind your business and keep your two cents to yourself. You never know why or what happened for the person to have to separate and grieve the relationship(s) for a lifetime.

ü©∏Ex: There are literally fucked up parents out here who will sell their daughters for sex to men, choose addiction over their child (and hurt them physically or mentally in the process), they‚Äôll protect family pedophiles, will repeatedly call their children ‚Äúbitches and hoes‚Äù.. all of this for NO reason other than they hate themselves, have went through their traumas, WON‚ÄôT change and are putting it on the child - it‚Äôs unsettling and is not good for growth. So yes - you telling someone ‚Äúbut that‚Äôs your mom‚Äù or ‚Äúthat‚Äôs your dad‚Äù after they‚Äôve dealt with possibly MAJOR mind altering traumas is insensitive af. Especially if their parent won‚Äôt hold themselves accountable in order for any reconciliation to occur.

üó£üó£üó£ if said parents or family refuse to change, refuse to admit their wrongs or shift their behavior - their child(ren) will HAVE EVERY RIGHT to remove themselves from their life to avoid further trauma (which can LITERALLY be embedded in our DNA üß¨) or disrespect.

Our children don‚Äôt ‚Äúowe‚Äù us anything when we birth them to Earth. We are simply here to guide them into the world and teach them how to take care of themselves (mind, body and spirit). When you fail to do that - YOU ARE NOT AN ASSET.

You choose your life and your blood has every right to choose theirs. Being üíØ and being mindful that we are all vessels on a journey (even the one doing the fuckery) just know that if you are somehow sidetracking someone from their peace; YOU MAY BE DISMISSED, regardless of the relationship.

"A year and a half ago my father passed away, and I was determined to be there. I was determined to watch him die. To hold his hand through his last breath. In the months leading up to his death as he developed dementia, I could tell that he was halfway here and halfway gone. He would talk about seeing his mother who had died 25 years ago, his sister, who had died 15 years ago, his daughter, my sister, who had died eight years prior ‚Äì they all visited him in his dying days. On my birthday he asked me to tell him about death. To explain what would happen to him. I explained that he would be loved in this world and in the next. And that is all he needed to hear. Ten days later, he died, but I was not around to see it. I‚Äôd just left for the night after sitting with him for three straight days listening to his death rattle. He passed once I walked away." ~ poet Danielle Badra

There is so much in these words to take in...how our dying die in their own time, no matter our wishes, our determination, our steadfast vision of how we hope it will be...Unlike what's often portrayed onscreen, there may be no profound final exchange, words that arrive just in time, like a blessing or needed release, no moment of "closure" to cling to beyond their final breath. But there are signs that death is near, including the facial expressions or murmurs directed at someone we cannot see, the conversations ‚Äî sometimes incomprehensible ‚Äî with those who have gone before. 

And there is love. The love that we can give and speak of long before they're dead, and the love that can attend them in their final days, whether we're there or not. An evolving presence ‚Äî a truth we both can carry, that blooms with warmth and vigor among the living and the dead.

I am not a therapist, this is not therapy, nor is this a replacement for therapy.

I created this space as a death worker who knows the overwhelming need to hold third spaces outside of the clinical/carceral setting and outside of home, and as a peer. 

In this space we acknowledge:

ü©∂we aren‚Äôt solving or advising
ü©∂the weight of these times as a human witnessing a multitude of gen0cides and atrocities 
ü©∂the grief illiteracy and suicidism of the society we are in
ü©∂and the effects of late stage capitalism

This is not education, this is to chip away at the isolation of living in these times and living alongside chronic suicidality.

This group goes for 75-90 minutes and we usually have up to 15 people. we begin with going over these boundaries and end with a few minutes of grounding talk to integrate one space to the other. 

In the middle .. open sharing. 

I bring a prompt into the space but nobody has to use it something like, ‚Äúwhat is the status of your suic¬°de right now‚Äù.

People can keep their cameras off, can leave before the set end time (though we ask for a little goodbye emoji or phrase in the chatbox), and there is no pressure to speak out loud but we encourage interaction with one another.

we don‚Äôt advise or solve. 
we don‚Äôt shame or judge. 
we listen.

Grief is a natural and complex reaction to the death of a loved one. Hospice of Redmond is here to provide compassionate assistance during this difficult time.

Many people choose to do end-of-life planning to minimize the burden of death on a loved one. The five main components of end-of-life planning include:

1. Advance Directive (living will)
2. Appointing a durable power of attorney (POA)
3. Last Will and Testament
4. Living Trust
5. POLST (Portable Orders for Life-Sustaining Treatment)

In our recent blog, we outline each component and discuss how to plan for the end of life. To learn more on this, head to our recent blog! Link in bio.

Living with a serious illness is a little easier with the right help. 

When diagnosed with a serious illness, many emotions come to the surface. These emotions can create feelings of unease, stress, anxiety, and uncertainty, which are not exclusively felt by the person who is sick. Family members and other caregivers often also struggle. 

Palliative care is specialized medical care for people with chronic or serious illnesses. Palliative care is different from other areas of medical care. Palliative care focuses on improving a person‚Äôs quality of life by relieving physical suffering. This is done by managing pain while also addressing a person‚Äôs emotional and spiritual needs.

Our Palliative Care program at Hospice of Redmond focuses on quality of life for someone facing chronic or serious illness. To learn more, please contact us. 
541-548-7483

Any honorably discharged veteran with ties to Oregon can have their name added to the Wall of Honor. 

Erected in 2013, this Wall is the only of its kind in Central Oregon. It stands 30 feet long and six feet high. Granite panels along the Wall are engraved with veterans‚Äô names, branches of service, years of service, and military conflict, if applicable. In addition to the flags of the Army, Navy, Marines, Coast Guard, and soon-to-be Space Force, the American flag and a POW/MIA flag wave proudly over the Wall. 

The Wall is one visible way we honor the heroes in the community and throughout Oregon. Families can pay their respects for the service of their loved ones. The veteran does not need to live in Oregon; they only need ties to the State. That can mean a family member who lives in Oregon and wants to teach their children to honor a family member close to home.

This beautiful monument is open to public viewing on the Hospice of Redmond grounds. To learn more about the Wall of Honor, contact us today! 
 541-548-7483

When living with a life-limiting illness, aging at home can be a challenging prospect. However, with the proper support and resources, it is possible to make your living situation more comfortable and manageable. 

Here are some tips:
1. Begin transitions care: Transitions is a non-medical program that supports you by providing recommendations to enhance you and your loved ones‚Äô quality of life. This can include connecting you with non-medical assistance through a network of trained volunteers.
2. Seek palliative care: Palliative care can help you manage symptoms and improve your quality of life. It can be utilized alongside curative treatment and provided by a specialist team of healthcare professionals in your home.
3. Consider hospice care: When no longer seeking curative treatment, hospice care should be considered. Hospice care can provide you and your family with medical, emotional, and spiritual support during the end-of-life process.

At Integra-Estates, we were incredibly privileged to attend the truly remarkable 25th St. Christopher's dinner, held at the impressive Goldsmiths Hall. This event is an essential fundraiser for the amazing work done by St. Christopher‚Äôs Hospice.

It was an honor to spend the evening in the company of such esteemed organisations, who contribute to St. Christopher's ongoing success. To be part of such a meaningful event was truly humbling.

Over the years, we've had the privilege of attending formal dinner events that include guest speakers. But hearing the heartfelt and inspiring story of Durone Stokes really left a lasting impact. His life was turned upside down when he lost his beloved brother at a young age. But through the support of St Christopher's Candle Child Bereavement Services, he received the care and understanding he so desperately needed. From the personal support tailored to his needs, to the music therapy that helped him channel his emotions and passions, Durone‚Äôs journey was a powerful reminder of the life-changing work St. Christopher's provides.

From Michael and myself at Integra-Estates, a heartfelt thank you to Durone for sharing such an insightful and moving story.

I meet a lot of new people each month with the job I have. I get to know their lives, their family, their story. What I can say is - for pretty much everyone-  life is beautiful and tragic and filled with laughter and tears and sorrow. There‚Äôs grief, regret and unspoken words. There‚Äôs love and hopes and dreams and visits. Then there‚Äôs annoyance and more heartbreak and life‚Äôs frustrations. And in between the intense moments, it‚Äôs all just everyday stuff: worrying about what‚Äôs for dinner, if the laundry‚Äôs been switched over and if the dog needs to go out. 

Just remember: no one matter what situation you‚Äôre going through, I can bet you‚Äôre not alone, even if it feels that way. 

Also remember: so many lives look pretty darn perfect on here/ news flash: they are not.

Anticipatory grief. 

The grief that isn‚Äôt spoken about. 
So what is it?

In short, Anticipatory grief is the grief you feel before a person has died. You‚Äôre grieving the current situation, the person they were, the life you had, and all the memories all at once. It can show up in a magnitude of ways, e.g. constant sadness (low mood), fear, guilt, anxiety, or physical symptoms such as: loss of appetite, trouble sleeping, pain in your chest, irritability, and so much more.

As someone supporting a griever, how can I help? 

‚Ä¢ Make them a meal (Curry, soup, Mac & cheese, lasagne, spag bowl, anything!)

‚Ä¢ Lend a hand with physical work e.g cleaning the bathrooms / kitchen / running errands / grabbing groceries.

‚Ä¢ Plan an outdoor activity with them (A walk, picnic)

‚Ä¢ Listen. Don‚Äôt try fix their grief. Just listen. 

‚Ä¢ Avoid statements like ‚Äúeverything happens for a reason‚Äù. Insensitive and shows ignorance. Instead focus on their feelings, and hold space for them to just be.

‚Ä¢ Send them a message. Not to have a good day. Rather, to have a day. Say you‚Äôre checking in to see they‚Äôve done their teeth, or managed to make the bed, or perhaps had a bite to eat. It‚Äôs not disregarding ‚Äògood‚Äô days, it‚Äôs being realistic and helping them achieve mundane tasks that feel so hard. 

‚Ä¢ Continue showing up for them. You don‚Äôt need to be perfect, simply present.

Educate yourself, be patient & show compassion. 

Hope this helps ‚ô•Ô∏è

‚ö†Ô∏è Content warning - death and bereavement 

üìª I have to admit to being a bit of a @bbcradio4 geek, though I‚Äôm not usually a fan of Desert Island Discs. But I happened across David Spiegelhalter‚Äôs episode and oh my, what a listen. Between the chuckles and anecdotes of this extraordinary man‚Äôs life, (plus pretty good record choices) I was moved to tears - deep guttural sobs - as he recounted the illness and death of his infant son. Absolutely heart-wrenching.

It‚Äôs a year today since we were told that my mum‚Äôs cancer was terminal, and that she only had a couple of weeks left. Of course you can‚Äôt compare grief, and the death of an aged parent is in marked contrast to the loss of a young child, but nonetheless I‚Äôve been thinking a lot recently about how ill-prepared we are for death, even when it‚Äôs expected.

So it was timely that straight after DID came the excellent On Consolation, telling the story of Cicely Saunders, who pioneered the modern hospice movement, including founding St Christopher‚Äôs Hospice in Sydenham, Lewisham. 

Another brilliant bit of radio, which gave a deeply moving insight into someone we should all thank for humanising death, and for giving the dying access to pain relief and holistic support.

One of the most poignant moments was her reply to patients distressed that their time was running out:

‚ÄúTime isn‚Äôt a matter of length,
It‚Äôs a matter of depth.
There‚Äôs always enough time if you can be with someone to share it‚Äù

We were lucky enough to have the support and resources to bring my mum home for her final weeks. The nhs pulled out all the stops despite it being the height of lockdown. The second image shows the hospital bed that was delivered to her home of 45 years, so that she could die in a familiar environment surrounded by her loved ones. It was a gruelling and traumatic time, but I‚Äôm so grateful that we were able to do it for her, and for us. Amidst the grief, a good death is something to be thankful for. 

.

Nature Walks & Reflection: Enjoy the calming beauty of autumn with a walk in the park. Take time to breathe, reflect, and find peace.

Cozy Journaling: Create a warm, inviting space with a blanket, tea, and a journal. Spend a few minutes each day writing down your thoughts or gratitude.

Common emotions:

Constant stress- Frustration, anger, or resentment

Guilt for feeling negative emotions

Risk of burnout

#NationalMammographyDay reminds us that early detection is key. Mammograms can catch issues before physical signs appear. With breast cancer as the most common cancer in women, regular screenings are crucial. Stay proactive for your health; some good reminders:

Visit your doctor and schedule a mammogram.

Encourage loved ones to schedule their mammograms.

Know your family history and share it with your physician.

Those at higher risk may need to start screening earlier.

Learn more about mammograms and early detection on the National Breast Cancer Foundation website; link in our bio.

Grief myth: Grief has a set timeframe, and you should move on after a certain period.

The Reality: Grief doesn't have a deadline. For some, it may take months; for others, it may take years. The intensity of grief may lessen over time, but the loss can continue to affect a person throughout their life. Everyone heals at their own pace, and allowing oneself to grieve fully is important without imposing a time limit.

The Top 5 Regrets of the Dying‚Ä¶

Shared by former palliative caregiver and best-selling author Bronnie Ware, these powerful insights remind us what truly matters:

‚ÄúI wish I‚Äôd had the courage to live true to myself, not the life of others.‚Äù

‚ÄúI wish I had let myself be happier.‚Äù

‚ÄúI wish I had the courage to express my feelings.‚Äù

‚ÄúI wish I had stayed in touch with my friends.‚Äù

‚ÄúI wish I hadn‚Äôt worked so hard.‚Äù

Time isn‚Äôt something we can save‚Äîonly spend. Let‚Äôs choose to spend it wisely.

Did you know there are four levels of hospice care:

Routine Home Care: Delivered at home or in a residential facility.

General Inpatient Care: For patients needing a higher level of care in a different setting.

Continuous Home Care: Provides 8-24 hours of support during crises to keep patients at home.

Respite Care: Temporary relief (up to 5 days) for the primary caregiver.

Have questions about hospice care? We're here to help. Reach out to learn more about the care options available. üîóAlso, check out our related blog; link in bio.

Stillwater Hospice takes an integrated approach to hospice care; as such, you are likely to meet a number of our team members throughout your hospice experience. They may include:

Healthcare Providers: Physicians, nurse practitioners, registered nurses, and other professionals coordinate patient care, working closely with primary or specialty providers to ensure high-quality medical treatment.

Hospice Medical Director: Our local Medical Director consults with healthcare providers, the hospice team, and patients, bringing expertise and community-based guidance.

Nurses: The Stillwater Hospice nursing team delivers direct patient care and educates families on end-of-life care and the dying process, offering crucial support to patients.

Social Workers: Essential for connecting patients to community resources, social workers provide counseling to comfort and support patients, caregivers, and families dealing with the impact of terminal illness.

Spiritual Care: Tailored to individual beliefs, spiritual care provides emotional comfort through pastoral visits and can arrange religious rites upon patient request.

Dorothy ‚ÄúDolly‚Äù Barkhouse.

My paternal grandmother is happiest when her hands are in the dirt. She feeds the birds daily, so religiously that the ducks came and KNOCKED on her door for dinner. She loves stones and crystals, picks up sand dollars and sea shells on the beach as gifts. She has been so strong moving literal boulders on the seashore‚Ä¶

I have come across the country to help her and my grandpa settle into assisted living. This is the first time I have been a Soul Companion, End of Life Carer for my own family. It has been heartbreaking and heartwarming and I‚Äôve only been here 24 hours. I am so thankful I can take this time with them. And so thankful for the friends here that look in on them. 

It‚Äôs never too early to talk about end of life wishes. It‚Äôs never too early to talk about transitions and types of care - to destigmatize and normalize care to prevent injury and undue stress.

How do you navigate pet grief?

Losing a loved one is one of the hardest experiences in life. In many cases, it's not a matter of taking time to 'get over it' or 'move on', but more of learning to live life without your special friend, even though it's hard and that hole they left will always be there. 

If you‚Äôre struggling with the loss of a pet:

‚Ä¢ Don‚Äôt try to fight it - it‚Äôs okay to feel overwhelmingly sad. Your feelings are meant to be felt.

‚Ä¢ Take the time you need to get back on your feet. Let employers, colleagues, family and friends know what you‚Äôre going through so you can take a step back.

‚Ä¢ Listen to your needs - Need a duvet day? Need to cancel your plans? Need to slow down a bit? Need to get away for a while? That‚Äôs okay.

‚Ä¢ Remember your grief is personal to you. You might want to talk about them a lot or you might feel like it's too painful. Let people know how they can support you.

‚Ä¢ Check out pet bereavement support services. The Blue Cross has lots of resources available, including email or webchats with their trained volunteers.

‚Ä¢ Speak to your doctor - you are NOT wasting your doctor's time if your mental health is suffering due to the loss of your pet. Pets are a huge part of our lives, and losing them can leave us feeling lost ourselves.

If you‚Äôve lost a pet, what advice would you share with someone going through it right now?

Why do we do it to ourselves?

Having animal companions brings us so much joy and fills our lives with fun, love, and often a bit of cheekiness! Our pets slot into our lives from day one, and it's like they've always been there, stealing our spot on the sofa or curled up on our laps or by our feet. Because they become family so quickly and seamlessly, it soon becomes impossible to imagine life without them‚Ä¶ and yet we know that, someday, we‚Äôll face the unbearable moment when we have to say goodbye forever and do life without them again.

This quote from Bones Would Rain from the Sky: Deepening our Relationship with Dogs, by Suzanne Clothier, perfectly sums up why we animal lovers put ourselves through the emotional rollercoaster of having furry family members time and time again ‚Äì no matter how unbearable it is at the end, we wouldn‚Äôt trade it for a life where they‚Äôd never crossed our path.

Our furry family members mean the world, so if you‚Äôd prefer to say your final goodbye in your own home, give us a call or send an email to info@forgetmenot-pets.co.uk. At Forget Me Not Pets, we provide a calm and personal home euthanasia service where you won't feel rushed, and your special friend won't feel stressed or anxious.

It‚Äôs your chance to share üòä

Pets give us so many special moments and treasured memories ‚Äì that silly expression they always had when they wanted to play, the way they ran away from the waves on their first trip to the beach, or that time when you walked in to find them curled up with your human children on the sofa.

When your pet has passed, it‚Äôs not easy to think about those memories, especially at first. The gap they‚Äôve left in your life feels so huge that it can never be filled. And perhaps it won‚Äôt ever truly be filled, because they can‚Äôt ever be replaced. But trust that there will be times when you can think about them and smile, remembering their funny ways and the love that you shared.

If you feel able to, we‚Äôd love to hear your favourite memories or moments with your pet, whether they‚Äôre still with us or have sadly passed. What did/do you love about them? What special little quirks did/do they have?

How do you support children with pet loss?

Books can be a great tool to help your child prepare for the procedure (if time allows) and process their grief afterwards. You might find that, if they‚Äôre old enough, they prefer to take time alone to read, or they might want your company, explanations and support. Try to make time to answer any questions that they have, and if you‚Äôre not sure of the answer, make a note to ask the vet ‚Äì we‚Äôre happy to help address any concerns they have.

Here are some of the best-rated books about pet loss for children, based on Amazon UK reviews this month:

1. The Invisible Leash by Patrick Karst ‚Äì this book is American, and that‚Äôs apparent in some of the language used. However, it‚Äôs still a very comforting, emotional and beautiful story.
2. The Rainbow Bridge: A Visit to Pet Paradise by Adrian Raeside ‚Äì this is a lovely story for children who have just experienced the loss of a pet. However, it does contain references to human death (so be prepared) and at the end of the story, the child gets a new pet, which might lead to an upsetting conversation if you don‚Äôt intend to.
3. My Pet Memory Book by S Wallace ‚Äì now this is a little bit different, in that it‚Äôs not for your child to read, but to write in and add to, documenting their pet‚Äôs life and memories. For many children, this could help them process their feelings. Be aware that some readers have found this book a little bit basic, so you might prefer to make your own memory book.
4. A Rainbow Bridge for Gus by Barbara Bareis Rigabar ‚Äì this book is sweet and simple, making it perfect for younger children and toddlers.

Have you found a particular book helpful in supporting you or your children through the loss of a pet? We‚Äôd love you to share your recommendations in the comments so that they might help other pet parents.

topPosts.caption:
It‚Äôs one of the most important and emotional decisions you have to make as a pet owner‚Ä¶

Saying goodbye, and choosing when and where is the hardest time for pet parents. It‚Äôs an emotional rollercoaster, especially if your pet is older or has chronic health problems that mean they have good days and bad days. In some ways, it would be easier to decide if our pet‚Äôs health deteriorated linearly, but in reality, it‚Äôs not that simple. One minute you could be thinking it‚Äôs time to say goodbye, and the next you see a hint of that sparkle they used to have, and it has you doubting yourself and wondering whether they have a little bit more time.

If this is you right now, and you‚Äôre struggling to decide whether it‚Äôs time to say your final farewell, look back at our previous posts ‚Äì we‚Äôve shared some useful information on how you know when the time is right, including a quality-of-life checklist and tools for monitoring your older boy or girl.

If you‚Äôre mulling over the idea of saying goodbye to your pet at home, but you have some reservations, why not head to our website? You‚Äôll find information about our service ‚Äì including the area covered and prices, and our contact details to book a visit. You can also read testimonials from other pet parents and find out more about what to expect. If after reading the website you‚Äôre still not sure, reach out to us ‚Äì we‚Äôre always happy to hear you and your pet‚Äôs story and help you decide what‚Äôs best for them.

Email us at info@forgetmenot-pets.co.uk, contact us by phone, or send us a DM.

Do you have questions about putting your pet to sleep?

Here are just a few of the most-searched questions on Google for pet parents considering saying their final goodbye to their pet:

Q: Can you get your pet put to sleep at home?
A: Yes, you absolutely can. Most vet practices will offer house calls when needed, but it‚Äôs often very difficult. That‚Äôs why I created Forget Me Not Pets, to provide a more relaxed, personal service.

Q: How do I tell my vet I want to euthanize my pet?
A: Remember that your vet always wants what‚Äôs best for both you and your pet. They‚Äôre on your team - if you‚Äôre having concerns about your pet‚Äôs health, wellbeing, or your ability to care for them, be open and honest.

Q: How can I help my pet pass away peacefully?
A: It‚Äôs really important not to try anything at home to help your pet pass away - this could be dangerous and cause them more suffering. Speak to your vet - our team are able to provide peaceful end of life care at home.

Q: How do I know when it‚Äôs time to put my pet down?
A: This is such a hard decision, but it‚Äôs one that your vet can support you with. If your pet is in pain, has mobility issues, or isn‚Äôt eating for a sustained period, these could be indicators that their quality of life isn‚Äôt as it should be.

Got a question about pet end of life care that you‚Äôd like answered? Send us a DM and we‚Äôll answer as many questions as we can and share the answers on our socials.

At Haven Hands Care, we provide compassionate and dignified live-in care for individuals in their final stages of life. Our dedicated team is committed to ensuring comfort, peace, and emotional support during this deeply personal time.
How We Support Clients:
Personalised Comfort: Tailored care plans to address physical needs and preferences, ensuring the highest level of comfort.
Emotional Support: Providing companionship and emotional reassurance to both clients and their families.
Pain Management: Collaborating with healthcare professionals to manage pain and symptoms effectively.
Family Support: Offering guidance and support to families, helping them navigate this challenging time with care and respect.
Our goal is to make this journey as peaceful and comfortable as possible. For more information on our end-of-life care services, please reach out to us. üíöüè†

We really think that the work that Longfield Care do in support of those diagnosed with life-limiting illnesses is so very important. And that the patient's family or close friends are also offered all kinds of wellbeing support. 

The Longfield team are now offering an Advance Care Planning group, running over several weeks. It is a free closed group - but once referred, you can sign up for all the sessions. Check the Longfield website for eligibility. Jane is a regular speaker at this group, providing support and information about funerals. Look out for a future post announcing when the next group will be starting.

Longfield has been running this pilot series of talks, therapies, exercise and creative workshops as part of their ongoing 'Wellbeing Programme'. This programme can be accessed by anyone who needs support during a life-limiting illness, whether it be the patient themselves, or those connected to the patient such as close family or friends.

Referral can be made by individuals, their families or healthcare provider. Check their website for eligibility:
https://longfield.org.uk/wellbeing-centre-2/ or head to @longfield_care

Look at our Valentine! February 14th she has been with us one year! 
She just seen the vet and is on antibiotics for a URI. Valentine is definetly a senior, 16ish maybe? She has had kidney disease and severe arthritis. 
We are waiting on some natural pain meds as well as kidney support. But as long as Valentine is eating, drinking, complaining and overall herself she will outlive her life here at the sanctuary. This is such an important question. But before you go to what you think is the obvious answer... ask these questions. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Can your Medical Power of Attorney guide your treatment the way YOU want and not the way they want? ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Can your Medical Power Attorney coordinate your care that ensures you get the best care that is also the safest care?‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Can your Medical Power Attorney do what is needed to take care of you, no matter what?‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
These questions are important to answer because it helps you decide the best person to be your Medical Power of Attorney.  It may not be your Spouse or even your Children. It may be your Friend, your Pastor or another family member. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Whomever you choose, just make sure it‚Äôs what is best for you. 
‚Å£
Please share this with someone who needs to hear this message.  And let me know your questions... I would love to help!

A gentleman came to the hospital  in what appeared to be a coma and he was having difficulty breathing. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
He had no family or friends that arrived with him at the hospital. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
So we, as hospitals will do, did everything to save this gentleman‚Äôs life.  He was placed on life support and given everything that could be given to extend his life. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
It was my job to find out who he is and who his family/friends are to inform them of this situation and to attempt to learn about his wishes at this time in his life. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
This is what I found out.  He lived alone and was estranged from his children. He had a long history of alcohol abuse  and preferred to be left alone. I found this out from his brother, who lived across the country. This brother was the closet person to this gentleman and was his MPOA. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
He provided me the copy of the Advanced Directive and that instructed his care team to focus totally on his comfort and allow him to die naturally, without life support but with pain management. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
If we did not have this, Pt would have lived the remaining time in his life in a nursing home with (most likely) artificial nutrition. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
He did not want this and we were able to honor his wishes with his Advanced Directive. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Have you completed your Advanced Directive?  What questions do you have about Advanced Directives? Let me know üëáüëá

Are you caring for someone in the last phase of their life?

At Carers Network, we empathise and can offer practical guidance at this difficult time.

When your loved one is approaching the end of their life, there may be issues for them, but also for you in your caring role. This might include discussing how and where they are cared for, coordinating health and financial affairs as well as declaring any specific wishes.

We aim to provide support that will assist adult unpaid carers to undertake their caring in a least stressful way as possible.

Contact us to find out more, and we‚Äôll put you in touch with Dolores, our End of Life Carers Project Manager.

Join me in celebrating life.

End of Life Care Ireland gathered outside Leinster House today. Great to meet my pal Karen Dempsey of @entheosireland there. 

The Oireachtas Committee on Dying with Dignity is meeting regularly and Senator Annie Hoey is representing us there. I understand it hopes to report by end of March.

Sometimes we don't appreciate a moment untill it is a distant memory.

The gift I was given, amongst all the pain, was knowing my time was limited. So I took the photos, I sipped the coffee and a held his hand.

Yesterday I stood at that same spot but all I felt was love for him and how proud I know he is of me.

Grief is wild but there is so much beauty in it. 

Celebrate your life. Celebrate your loved ones.

Lifetime of repressed anger /emotions / sensory outbursts

" don't show it" . 

Our emotions can free us or they can cage us. 

Accept them.. release them so they do not control  you. 

If you can't freely scream or you still feel the need to muffle it , grab a pillow and let it go out.
Let it naturally flow.. screams can turn to rage or heartbreak, let it show itself. 

My release was changed to love when my little buddy was worried and came to make sure I'm ok, as he always does.

Did you know that yesterday was World Hospice and Palliative Care Day? ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
The goal of this day is to bring focus on what Hospice and Palliative Care is and how important it can be to people with serious illness. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Hospice and Palliative care assists people in improving the quality of life their life when they are affected by serious health problems. Those that have life-limiting illnesses have the right to be cared for in the way that best suits their needs. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
I have worked with people with serious illness for over 20 years. There is nothing more out of a person‚Äôs control when they are diagnosed with a serious illness.  This type of care gives control back and decisions are made based on what is important to you. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Please like this post if you agree that Hospice and Palliative Care can be so helpful.  I would love to hear how this type of care has helped you or someone you know. üëáüëá

I may not have focused on building wealth in this life and planning for retirement- but I sure have focused on building a life that lifts me up and excites me. I have planned for when my hands won‚Äôt massage anymore and I want to research and get paid to research the effects of alternative therapies for people who are stressed to the max and on the treadmill of life. 
I don‚Äôt get bored. I don‚Äôt go thru ground hog day. I make shit happen and I fill my brain with cool stuff every week.

Looking back on the Podcast interviews that I have been very grateful to be part of. üôè‚ú®ü©∑

A Sudden Death is by far one of the most overwhelming, stressful and painful ways to lose a loved one. Most often a sudden death is defined by an accident of one kind or another (by car, fall, drowning, etc), cardiac arrest, an aneurysm, an allergic reaction, drug overdose or suicide. Most often (but not always) the time of death is pronounced in a hospital setting and the family is then later given notice of their loved one‚Äôs passing. This type of end of life scenario needs support and resources that can be hard for a family to navigate on their own given the shock and overwhelm of a sudden death. 

Hiring and getting a Death Doula on board for situations such as these is a perfect fit for the best after death care outcomes. A Death Doula can not only help support the family navigate the turmoil and stress of the situation but can act as front contact person for the calls and arraignments they need to take place after a sudden death has occurred. 

With a Death Doula‚Äôs knowledge, connection to community, local funeral homes and body‚Äôs disposition options as some of there offered skill sets, a Death Doula can help with the funeral planning, after death care resources and choice/s and referrals, as well as emotional support and companionship during the process. 

A Death Doula‚Äôs understanding in these areas of End of Life Care and their innate way of knowing what to do, when maybe a family may not know what to do, is why Death Doulas are so needed and should be called upon to help lessen the trauma and overwhelm in even the unimaginable sudden death circumstance. 

Would love to hear your thoughts below in the comments üëá

"Dying is an integral part of life, as natural and predictable as being born. But whereas birth is cause for celebration, death has become a dreaded and unspeakable issue to be avoided by every means possible in our modern society. Perhaps it is that death reminds us of our own human vulnerability in spite of all our technological advances. We may be able to delay it, but we can not escape it. We, no less than other, non-rational animals, are destined  to die at the end of our lives. And death strikes indiscriminately- it cares not at all for the status or position of the ones it chooses; everyone must die, whether rich or poor, famous or unknown. Even good deeds will not excuse their doers from the sentence of death; the good die as often as the bad. It is perhaps this inevitable and unpredictable quality that makes death so frightening to many people. Especially those who put a high value on being control of their own existence are offended by the thought that they, too, are subject to the forces of death." ü§çüôèüèºüíöüïäüíú

70% of people express the wish to die at home but only 14% of people do.
Why is this?
Usually it is due to lack of information, support, services in place and a lack of preparation and thorough planning.
Yes it is 100% safe, legal and possible to die in the comfort of your own home but to ensure this is carried out in the best possible way you do need to know what is involved and what it will actually require of you and also what type of support you will need to do this successfully.
The role of End of Life doulas will support you and help you to navigate the end of life care options, working alongside your GP and community care services.
Early conversations can free up your mind so that you can focus on being a family member and not just a carer role. üçÉ

Death Doula‚Äôs have a very much needed presence at the deathbed. We help create environments of peace, stillness and vulnerability through being intentionally grounded within a very tender and raw space. It is our job to make sure we are ‚Äúholding the rim‚Äù in these dying experiences for the dying and their families in a way that helps to allow whatever needs to unfold in that space to occur in a safe and memorable way. 

Hiring a Death Doula, just for this purpose solely, is worthwhile for all parties involved. There is a certain type of magic in experiencing what a Death Doula can offer in these dying spaces - through their heightened awareness in the room, by allowing their calm grounded nervous systems to be available to the dying and the family and all the while keeping the most watchful eye on the dying. Every dying experience is different and unique and a Death Doula is a wonderful companion to help facilitate the process along üíñ

I love hearing families talk about how beautiful and memorable their loved ones last days of life were because they were able to experience this type of care during it. It takes what could be a very scary and overwhelming experience to a very graceful and magical one ‚ú®

NO.... But YES... confused Yet??
‚Å£
Palliative Care literally means to ‚Äúmake easy.‚Äù 
‚Å£
Technically both types of care work to make things easier for people with serious illness. 
‚Å£
Hospice care is a SPECIALIZED Form of Palliative Care that only happens in the last 6 months of life. 
‚Å£
Palliative Care is a form of care that can happen when a person is diagnosed with a serious illness and can remain in place while receiving curative treatment. 
‚Å£
Swipe üëâ to see the chart for a visual explanation. 
‚Å£
Please save this for future reference and share it with someone who needs this information.

This is such an important question. But before you go to what you think is the obvious answer... ask these questions. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Can your Medical Power of Attorney guide your treatment the way YOU want and not the way they want? ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Can your Medical Power Attorney coordinate your care that ensures you get the best care that is also the safest care?‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
‚Ä¢ Can your Medical Power Attorney do what is needed to take care of you, no matter what?‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
These questions are important to answer because it helps you decide the best person to be your Medical Power of Attorney.  It may not be your Spouse or even your Children. It may be your Friend, your Pastor or another family member. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Whomever you choose, just make sure it‚Äôs what is best for you. 
‚Å£
Please share this with someone who needs to hear this message.  And let me know your questions... I would love to help!

A gentleman came to the hospital  in what appeared to be a coma and he was having difficulty breathing. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
He had no family or friends that arrived with him at the hospital. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
So we, as hospitals will do, did everything to save this gentleman‚Äôs life.  He was placed on life support and given everything that could be given to extend his life. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
It was my job to find out who he is and who his family/friends are to inform them of this situation and to attempt to learn about his wishes at this time in his life. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
This is what I found out.  He lived alone and was estranged from his children. He had a long history of alcohol abuse  and preferred to be left alone. I found this out from his brother, who lived across the country. This brother was the closet person to this gentleman and was his MPOA. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
He provided me the copy of the Advanced Directive and that instructed his care team to focus totally on his comfort and allow him to die naturally, without life support but with pain management. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
If we did not have this, Pt would have lived the remaining time in his life in a nursing home with (most likely) artificial nutrition. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
He did not want this and we were able to honor his wishes with his Advanced Directive. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£
Have you completed your Advanced Directive?  What questions do you have about Advanced Directives? Let me know üëáüëá

My oldest dog, Mugsy, has never known life without Spike until a few weeks ago. For me, it was over 17 and a half years with that really good black and white cat. I rescued his mom when I was 22 and he was born shortly thereafter. Pretty much my entire adult life has included his heavy footsteps (even when he got down to 7 pounds), screaming (he was literally the loudest cat on earth) and boundless affection. Despite a few strokes over the last 9 months he was doing pretty well. But a few weeks ago he had a fairly big stroke leading to a rapid decline. Euthanasia is tricky to navigate but we are lucky to have an exceptional vet who never judged us and instead gave us many things to think about. I hope this post helps even one person in their dealing with a pet nearing the end of its life. .

I love delivering TLC End of Life Care workshops. And this right here is one of the reasons why I love it so so much üôèüèº To know how each person is affected by it in a healing way, to know the deep and profound effect it can have and to know someone now feels comforted brings me so much joy and gratitude üí´ 
 
These workshops provide valuable information about death and dying and how we can be present and support the process. They do all this in a very human, real and honest way. And a way that resonates with each of us. It is not about teaching everyone the medical stuff or how to be a Soul Midwife, it is about every human having the understanding of a very human experience, and the only one that is guaranteed and that we will ALL go through and be part of üôèüèº
